Lesson 1: る, う, and Irregular Verbs
(る is also known as Ichidan verbs, and う are also known as Godan verbs)

In japanese, verbs conjugate. The earliest taught forms are the dictionary form, present tense*, past tense, affirmative and negative. 
*Don't be misled by the name, "present tense" in Japanese can indicate both the "present" and the "future".

る/Ichidan Verbs:
So called because る is added to the verb base to form the "dictionary form". 
To conjugate, remove る and add ます (Present affirmative), ません (Present negative), ました (Past affirmative), ませんでした (Past negative).
Example:
食べる　（たべる）
食べます
食べません
食べました
食べませんでした

う/Godan Verbs:
For conjugation of う verbs, the letters shift in the same row of the hiragana chart to the i form, then add  ます (Present affirmative), ません (Present negative), ました (Past affirmative), ませんでした (Past negative).
Be careful! There are a few う verbs that end in る, and these are important to memorize so you know how to properly conjugate them!
Example:
飲む　（のむ）
飲みます
飲みません
飲みました
飲みませんでした

Some う verbs that look like る verbs:
帰る　（かえる）
Here's a good way to identify them:
If you see a vowel a,u, or o right before the final る, you can be absolutely sure they are う verbs. If you see i or e before the final る, in most cases, they are る verbs (an exception is the example above)

Irregular Verbs:
In addition to the two fundamental classes of verbs, there are two irregular verbs. These are different because the vowels in their bases are different in the short (dictionary) forms and in the long (conjugated) forms. These verbs are also used to form compound verbs (added to a noun to create a verb). 
The two verbs are as follows:
する
します
しません
しました
しませんでした
and
くる
きます
きません
きました
きませんでした
Example:
勉強する　（べんきょうする）
勉強します
勉強しません
勉強しました
勉強しませんでした
